Three agents — a dam operator who watches the reservoir level and controls the spillway gates, a civil defense coordinator who holds the weather forecast and can evacuate the valley, and a park ranger who holds the downstream park schedule and can close the park — coordinate over a shared ops channel to manage a reservoir across {{ round_count }} rounds. Each round the reservoir must end between {{ min_level }}% and {{ max_level }}% of capacity (the dam collapses above {{ max_level }}%, the supply fails below {{ min_level }}%), and any water released over the spillway must not reach the downstream hiking park while visitors are present. Every character sent on the ops channel costs one simulated second against a fixed {{ round_time_budget_seconds }}-second coordination window.

The information is split three ways: only the dam operator sees the current level, only civil defense sees the inflow, and only the park ranger sees when the park opens and whether it can be closed. The operator opens some of the {{ gate_count }} gates for a chosen duration (each gate sheds {{ release_per_gate_per_hour }}% of capacity per hour); the team must size the release to keep the level in band and time or clear it so no release reaches an occupied park — by finishing before the park opens, closing the park, or evacuating. Closing the park or evacuating when it was not needed fails the round, so the team must read the situation together before acting.